Lesbians stormed the BBC to protest it. Twenty thousand Mancunians marched against it. Ian McKellen came out as gay to fight it. You'd be hard pressed to find a recent British law more controversial (and callous) than Section 28.

Section 28 is the vaguely worded legislation that prohibited local authorities and schools from “promoting” homosexuality or funding much-needed LGBTQ+ initiatives from 1988 right up until 2003. 

To celebrate Pride in London, join us to reflect on the impact of Section 28, 30 years since it was first passed into law, with a screening of 'We Have Rather Been Invaded' by film maker Ed Webb-Ingall. After the screening, there will be a discussion on the law's effect on the many of us who grew up under it and the ongoing role of queer activism.

eventDescription.en-GB:
Join us for an evening of fun, laughter, Pride, and Morris dancing! 

New Esperance Morris are pleased to invite you to the Pride edition of one of our Morris dancing taster sessions. You might have seen us in the 2018 Pride parade, as winners of the Pride in London Parade Team Award last year, or you may just have a burning passion for Morris dancing! 

Our Pride taster session will be at our usual practice hall (Queensborough Community Centre, Southwark), at our usual time of 7.30 - 9.30pm on Wednesday 11th July. You'll get a chance to learn about Morris, watch a quick showcase dance, and spend most of the session having a go yourself - first you'll learn the basic steps, and then build up to dancing with our experienced team.  You'll be doing at least one dance with hankies and one with sticks (don't panic, we'll show you how!), so please wear comfortable clothes and shoes that are suitable for active dancing. If you have a disability and would like to talk to us about any needs that may arise, please contact us via our website. If you wish to come as a musician, please let us know your instrument and ability so that we can provide music for you. 

Could you be the next great morris dancer? Who knows... but we can promise an evening of fun, great company, enthusiasm, new skills, challenges, and Pride - with bells on! 

New Esperance Morris are a women's Morris team who are proud to champion the living tradition of Morris and to celebrate members from many identities under the Pride umbrella... and if you share our love of fun, our ethos, and a passion for dancing, then we welcome you to join us! We want to meet keen dancers, musicians, and friends regardless of race, nationality, sexuality, gender identity, age, disability, culture, or religion. Please see our website for more details and FAQs.  https://newesperance.wordpress.com/

Please wear comfortable clothes and shoes suitable for active dancing.

accessibilityDetails.en-GB: If you have access needs which may affect your experience of our event, please contact us so that we can help make sure the session is as accessible and enjoyable as possible. eventDescription.en-GB:
The second installment of Queer Asia’s annual Film Festival focuses on the theme of Bodies X Borders to be screened in June 2018 in London. Bodies X Borders evokes frames of visualising queer bodies transgressing (norms, nations, identities) in a fast changing global world.

‘Queer’ Asia Film Festival is back with five days of films from all over Asia. The film festival this year show cases 30 films including the first ever ‘Queer’ Asia Short Shorts, a collection of 22 short films from countries including China, India, Myanmar, Thailand, and Lebanon. The collection of films this year address ‘Queer’ Asia’s thematic focus on ‘Bodies X Borders’ as they trace Asian diasporas in transnational locations such as in Crossing Bridges (Canada/Indonesia) and the mediation of dangerous national borders in Screaming Goats (Thailand); or imagine the complexities of racialised bodies and Islam within European urban spaces in A Post-Ottoman Trilogy (Skopje, Sarajevo, and Salonika), or even build solidarity and learning between the LGBTQ movements in Asia and South America with a featured documentary from Argentina. The Film Festival is co-hosted at The British Museum and SOAS, University of London from the 24th to 29th of June, 2018.

accessibilityDetails.en-GB: Tickets are necessary, visitor passes at registration or security at SOAS.

We are delighted to invite you to Tenpin Bowling with Pride, for an evening of great bowling, banter and beers with other members of the LGBT+ community!

You will get to play two games of bowling with other friendly people in an attitude-free and clique-free environment. 

It's a great opportunity to socialise, have fun and make some new friends! We also make sure there's a great Pride playlist of tunes lined-up and we crank the volume up too!

THE PLAN OF ACTION...

We gather at 7pm and aim to start the first round of bowling games around 8pm.

THE DEAL...

The cost is £13 for two games. When you sign in with us, you will also be provided with one free strip of raffle tickets for the prize draw that will take place during the evening. Our top prize is a £50 bar tab at Village Soho. Additional prizes include Champagne, Prosecco, wine and chocolates.

Your bowling ability, or lack of it, is not something to be embarrassed about when joining us, as we mainly play for fun, to have a laugh and to be social. You can even avoid changing into bowling shoes and simply play in your own footwear, as most of our guys currently do!

JOIN US...

...WITH A FRIEND OR TWO: Grab a mate or two and bring them along for a great night out. We can make sure you are put in a lane together. Simply let us know on the night that you are together when you are handing in your game allocation slips.

Much-acclaimed 70-minute solo play about the life of Quentin Crisp. Openly gay as early as the 1930s, Quentin spent decades being beaten up on London’s streets simply for his refusal to be anything less than himself. His steadfast courage, and the powerful philosophy that evolved from those experiences, continue to inspire to the present day. "Naked Hope" is a gloriously uplifting salute to a true one-off, and a timely reminder of the urgent necessity to live every day as your true self.

It's performed by Mark Farrelly, whose West End credits include "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?" at Trafalgar Studios. Doing two special performances in central London to celebrate Pride as part of a UK tour. Will be holding a collection for Pride at the end of both performances. eventDescription.en-GB:
Dates and times:
Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday, Sunday - 7:45pm 
Saturday & Thursday - 3pm, 7.45pm 


'Lonely Planet' is a heartfelt, funny and moving play set in an unnamed American city during the AIDS epidemic in the 80’s. It focuses on the relationship between Jody, a cautious and thoughtful man who insulates himself in the map store he owns; and Carl, a frequent visitor to the store with an unusually vivid imagination and multiple, ever-changing occupations. Carl notices Jody has been isolating himself from the world and starts bringing chairs into his shop to convince him to confront the fears which prevent him from leaving his store. The story follows these two characters as they cope with their friends dying of AIDS, Jody’s fear of going for a checkup and the prejudice against people who are HIV positive. 

The play would run from the __14th of June til the 7th of July, 2018__ at the __Trafalgar Studio 2__ (90 seats), during Gay Pride. The Cast and Crew include:  

Director: Ian Brown - Previous artistic director of the West Yorkshire Playhouse in Leeds and Traverse Theatre in Edinburgh.
Lighting Designer: Will Scarnell - A senior stage management tutor at LAMDA and freelancing lighting designer.
Sound Designer: Peter West
Stage Manager: Rachel Graham
Jody: Alex McMorran
Carl: Aaron Vodovoz

eventDescription.en-GB:
Much-acclaimed 70-minute solo play about the life of Quentin Crisp. Openly gay as early as the 1930s, Quentin spent decades being beaten up on London’s streets simply for his refusal to be anything less than himself. His steadfast courage, and the powerful philosophy that evolved from those experiences, continue to inspire to the present day. "Naked Hope" is a gloriously uplifting salute to a true one-off, and a timely reminder of the urgent necessity to live every day as your true self.

It's performed by Mark Farrelly, whose West End credits include "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?" at Trafalgar Studios. Doing two special performances in central London to celebrate Pride as part of a UK tour. Will be holding a collection for Pride at the end of both performances. Previous collections have totalled several thousand pounds.

Press: ★★★★ Time Out, The Stage, Metro, British Theatre Guide, Reviews Hub

HIV and LGBT history are impossible to separate, which is why we’ve invited the guys from Terrence Higgins Trust to take over our Pride pop-up to find out more about their work. You’ll also be able to pick up a free HIV self test kit where you can test yourself at home and get a result within 15 minutes.

Rebecca Tallon-De Havilland , who’s been living with HIV for over 30 years, will share her powerful story at 7pm. Rebecca received her diagnosis as part of the standard tests before her gender reassignment surgery back in 1986.

There will also be the chance to hear from Chamut Kifetew from HIV Prevention England about the charity’s Can’t Pass It On campaign, which is all about raising awareness that people living with HIV who are on effective treatment can’t pass it on – with or without a condom. As I’m sure you’ll agree, this is incredible news and brilliant progress.

There will also be information about It Starts With Me’s summer campaign which focuses on all the ways you can now stop HIV – condoms, regular testing, PrEP and HIV treatment.

locationName.en-GB: SET venue, 27A Dalston Lane London, England, E8 3DF

eventDescription.en-GB:
This event is free with donations going to the new London LGBTQ+ Community Centre in Hackney

[Donate here](https://www.crowdfunder.co.uk/londonlgbtqcentre "This event is free with donations going to the new London LGBTQ+ Community Centre in Hackney")

[Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/events/206776580120860/ "Facebook")

Lesbians stormed the BBC to protest it. Twenty thousand Mancunians marched against it. Ian McKellen came out as gay to fight it. You'd be hard pressed to find a recent British law more controversial (and callous) than Section 28.

Section 28 is the vaguely worded legislation that prohibited local authorities and schools from “promoting” homosexuality or funding much-needed LGBTQ+ initiatives from 1988 right up until 2003. 

To celebrate Pride in London, join us to reflect on the impact of Section 28, 30 years since it was first passed into law, with a screening of 'We Have Rather Been Invaded' by film maker Ed Webb-Ingall. After the screening, there will be a discussion on the law's effect on the many of us who grew up under it and the ongoing role of queer activism.

On 10th and 11th June, at Theatre503, a group of Brazilian and non-Brazilian artists will launch the show, Brazil Diversity. The proposal is "to bring to the stage the conflicts and characters that don’t appear in the Brazilian soap operas, a Brazil far beyond samba and football," according to curators Marcia Zanelatto and Rogerio Correa. The show is dedicated to 40 years of the LGBT movement in Brazil.

There are 8 short plays altogether, 6 new ones and 2 from the original project, written by Brazilian playwrights, staged in English by Brazilian and non-Brazilian directors and actors. The idea is to bring together art and activism for the visibility, achievement and maintenance of LGBT+ rights worldwide. "We live in the world that is more and more LGBT+, but stories continue to be dominated by heterosexual narratives and protagonists. We have to revaluate that - after all, Brazil is the country that kills the highest number of LGBT people in the world", says Marcia Zanelatto, the creator of the project’s Brazilian version and co-curator and producer of the British version.

eventDescription.en-GB:
This walk was developed last year to commemorate 50 years since the partial decriminalisation of homosexual acts in England and Wales. It starts by setting the scene in Tudor England, when the Buggery Act was introduced by Henry the Eighth. 

We then discuss the emergence of the homosexual subculture and chart its progression throughout history, from molly houses in the 18th century, the introduction of public conveniences in the Victorian period, the emergence of a strong drug culture in the 20th century, the setbacks suffered throughout the 1980s, the boom time around the turn of the last century, and the current demise of queer spaces in London. 

Highlights include a Victorian gay brothel where an heir to the throne was embroiled in a scandal, a lesbian club which was over-run with punks, and the cheek flushing nick-names a certain socialite gave to his harem of boy-servants. 

The walk takes approx 2 hours, starts at Goodge Street Station and finishes in Soho Square.

eventDescription.en-GB:
Join us for an evening of fun, laughter, Pride, and Morris dancing! 

New Esperance Morris are pleased to invite you to the Pride edition of one of our Morris dancing taster sessions. You might have seen us in the 2018 Pride parade, as winners of the Pride in London Parade Team Award last year, or you may just have a burning passion for Morris dancing! 

Our Pride taster session will be at our usual practice hall (Queensborough Community Centre, Southwark), at our usual time of 7.30 - 9.30pm on Wednesday 11th July. You'll get a chance to learn about Morris, watch a quick showcase dance, and spend most of the session having a go yourself - first you'll learn the basic steps, and then build up to dancing with our experienced team.  You'll be doing at least one dance with hankies and one with sticks (don't panic, we'll show you how!), so please wear comfortable clothes and shoes that are suitable for active dancing. If you have a disability and would like to talk to us about any needs that may arise, please contact us via our website. If you wish to come as a musician, please let us know your instrument and ability so that we can provide music for you. 

Could you be the next great morris dancer? Who knows... but we can promise an evening of fun, great company, enthusiasm, new skills, challenges, and Pride - with bells on! 

New Esperance Morris are a women's Morris team who are proud to champion the living tradition of Morris and to celebrate members from many identities under the Pride umbrella... and if you share our love of fun, our ethos, and a passion for dancing, then we welcome you to join us! We want to meet keen dancers, musicians, and friends regardless of race, nationality, sexuality, gender identity, age, disability, culture, or religion. Please see our website for more details and FAQs.  https://newesperance.wordpress.com/

Please wear comfortable clothes and shoes suitable for active dancing.

accessibilityDetails.en-GB: If you have access needs which may affect your experience of our event, please contact us so that we can help make sure the session is as accessible and enjoyable as possible. For answers to commonly asked questions, see here: https://newesperance.wordpress.com/contact/taster-sessions/

eventDescription.en-GB:
The second installment of Queer Asia’s annual Film Festival focuses on the theme of Bodies X Borders to be screened in June 2018 in London. Bodies X Borders evokes frames of visualising queer bodies transgressing (norms, nations, identities) in a fast changing global world.

‘Queer’ Asia Film Festival is back with five days of films from all over Asia. The film festival this year show cases 30 films including the first ever ‘Queer’ Asia Short Shorts, a collection of 22 short films from countries including China, India, Myanmar, Thailand, and Lebanon. The collection of films this year address ‘Queer’ Asia’s thematic focus on ‘Bodies X Borders’ as they trace Asian diasporas in transnational locations such as in Crossing Bridges (Canada/Indonesia) and the mediation of dangerous national borders in Screaming Goats (Thailand); or imagine the complexities of racialised bodies and Islam within European urban spaces in A Post-Ottoman Trilogy (Skopje, Sarajevo, and Salonika), or even build solidarity and learning between the LGBTQ movements in Asia and South America with a featured documentary from Argentina. The Film Festival is co-hosted at The British Museum and SOAS, University of London from the 24th to 29th of June, 2018.

eventDescription.en-GB:
We are delighted to invite you to Tenpin Bowling with Pride, for an evening of great bowling, banter and beers with other members of the LGBT+ community!

You will get to play two games of bowling with other friendly people in an attitude-free and clique-free environment. 

It's a great opportunity to socialise, have fun and make some new friends! We also make sure there's a great Pride playlist of tunes lined-up and we crank the volume up too!

THE PLAN OF ACTION...

We gather at 7pm and aim to start the first round of bowling games around 8pm.

THE DEAL...

The cost is £13 for two games. When you sign in with us, you will also be provided with one free strip of raffle tickets for the prize draw that will take place during the evening. Our top prize is a £50 bar tab at Village Soho. Additional prizes include Champagne, Prosecco, wine and chocolates.

IF YOU ARE NEW....

If you're new, then you are very welcome to come along and join! Just RSVP and find us in the venue on the night and you'll receive a warm welcome!

Your bowling ability, or lack of it, is not something to be embarrassed about when joining us, as we mainly play for fun, to have a laugh and to be social. You can even avoid changing into bowling shoes and simply play in your own footwear, as most of our guys currently do!

JOIN US...

...ON YOUR OWN: Don't be worried about coming along on your own. You won't be left feeling like billy-no-mates! We will make sure you're in a lane with with other people who, like you, found the courage to come along unaccompanied and join in the fun.

...WITH A FRIEND OR TWO: Grab a mate or two and bring them along for a great night out. We can make sure you are put in a lane together. Simply let us know on the night that you are together when you are handing in your game allocation slips.

...AS AS GROUP: Come along with a bunch of friends and all bowl together in the same lane. We place up to 8 people max per lane and can give you a neighbouring lane if you have a bigger group. Just hand your game allocation sheets in together.

Wednesday 1 August 2018 - 7pm to 10.15pm__

eventDescription.en-GB:
Much-acclaimed 70-minute solo play about the life of Quentin Crisp. Openly gay as early as the 1930s, Quentin spent decades being beaten up on London’s streets simply for his refusal to be anything less than himself. His steadfast courage, and the powerful philosophy that evolved from those experiences, continue to inspire to the present day. "Naked Hope" is a gloriously uplifting salute to a true one-off, and a timely reminder of the urgent necessity to live every day as your true self.

It's performed by Mark Farrelly, whose West End credits include "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?" at Trafalgar Studios. Doing two special performances in central London to celebrate Pride as part of a UK tour. Will be holding a collection for Pride at the end of both performances. Previous collections have totalled several thousand pounds.

Press: ★★★★ Time Out, The Stage, Metro, British Theatre Guide, Reviews Hub

eventDescription.en-GB:
Dates and times:
Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday, Sunday - 7:45pm 
Saturday & Thursday - 3pm, 7.45pm 


'Lonely Planet' is a heartfelt, funny and moving play set in an unnamed American city during the AIDS epidemic in the 80’s. It focuses on the relationship between Jody, a cautious and thoughtful man who insulates himself in the map store he owns; and Carl, a frequent visitor to the store with an unusually vivid imagination and multiple, ever-changing occupations. Carl notices Jody has been isolating himself from the world and starts bringing chairs into his shop to convince him to confront the fears which prevent him from leaving his store. The story follows these two characters as they cope with their friends dying of AIDS, Jody’s fear of going for a checkup and the prejudice against people who are HIV positive. 

The play would run from the __14th of June til the 7th of July, 2018__ at the __Trafalgar Studio 2__ (90 seats), during Gay Pride. The Cast and Crew include:  

Director: Ian Brown - Previous artistic director of the West Yorkshire Playhouse in Leeds and Traverse Theatre in Edinburgh.
Lighting Designer: Will Scarnell - A senior stage management tutor at LAMDA and freelancing lighting designer.
Sound Designer: Peter West
Stage Manager: Rachel Graham
Jody: Alex McMorran
Carl: Aaron Vodovoz
